observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to:
Require the MAO and the MGSO, with the assistance from the Municipal Engineering Office (MEO), to continue reconciling the noted discrepancies, investigate immediately the causes thereof, and effect accordingly the necessary adjustments in the records. Thereafter, maintain properly the required accounting and property records;
Direct the Inventory Committee to reconcile the results of the physical count with the property and accounting records immediately after the physical inventory taking. The inventory listing of the PPE items shall be checked with the PCs as against the PPELCs and the total thereof shall be compared with those in the GL. All discrepancies between physical and book inventories must be investigated, cleared and reconciled immediately as required under Section C.3, Chapter V of the Manual on Property Custodianship;
Require the MA to continue identifying PPE items acquired in current and prior years which are being used by other agencies and draw appropriate journal entry vouchers to derecognize these from the books after proper transfer/donation thereof; and
Assign temporarily to other personnel some workloads of the members of the Inventory Committee during the conduct of physical count as required under Section 5.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the LCE:
Call the attention of the previous accountant to turn-over pertinent records to the incumbent MA;
Require the MA and Municipal Treasurer (MT) to retrieve information on CAs from journals, cashbooks, and reports of checks issued as secondary evidence pertaining to outstanding CAs;
Require the MA to maintain SL for CA per accountable employee/official;
Require the AOs to present their triplicate copies of LRs, if any, as proof of liquidation as required under Section 53 of Manual on NGAS for LGUs;
Send demand letters to AOs with outstanding CAs; and
If exhausting all administrative remedies proved futile and liquidation of the subject CAs is remote, file request to write-off of these CAs supported with the required documents in accordance with COA Circular No. 93-404.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Require the MTO to prepare the list of all delinquent RPT and market stallholders and submit the same to the Sangguniang Bayan of MGB with request for assistance in enforcing remedies for collection of those delinquent accounts;
Direct the MT and Public Market Administrator to establish and maintain detailed records of delinquent accounts to facilitate collection and monitoring;
Require the MTO to devise collection strategies to ensure prompt payment of market dues by stallholders to increase revenue collections;
Direct the MA to issue demand letters to all delinquent stallholders to settle immediately their unpaid market dues.  Otherwise, impose sanctions as provided under the Revenue Code and Municipal Ordinances; and
Require the Public Market Administrator to diversify the business establishments in the Public Market and devise a plan designating strategic places suitable or appropriate for each class/kind of business.

We recommended that the LCE:
Demand from the previous MA to turn over/surrender financial records to the incumbent MA;
Require the MA and MT to locate the missing disbursement vouchers for the unrecorded cleared checks. Otherwise, direct the MT to retrieve information from the cashbook and Reports of Checks Issued for the unrecorded disbursements and furnish the information to the MA for recognition;
Direct the MA to request bank statements from the AGDB for the two bank accounts and prepare the corresponding BRS;
Require the MA to prepare appropriate adjusting entries for the identified errors and other book reconciling items; and
Require the MA to prepare regularly the BRS for all bank accounts.
Management Comment:
The Management has already tried to comply with the audit observations but encountered some difficulties such as non-cooperation of previous MA to turn-over properly the related documents.

We recommended and the LSB agreed to:
Prepare and approve strictly the SEF Budget not later than October 31 of the current year;
Include SEF cash savings from prior years in the preparation of the annual budget and enact a supplemental budget covering cash savings from the immediately preceding year as part of the current year’s SEF Budget to finance other priority PPAs;
Conduct meeting at least once a month to realize optimal utilization of the SEF Fund;
Incorporate priority SEF PPAs in the AIP; and
Utilize the SEF Budget efficiently and effectively by optimally implementing all identified PPAs.

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendations that Management:

Require the Municipal General Services Officer (MGSO) and the Municipal Accounting Office to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;

Require the Municipal Accounting Office concerned personnel to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL account balances and the MGSO concerned personnel to keep corresponding Property Cards for control purposes;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to continue tracing back prior years’ acquisitions of PPE to have a complete detail of the PPE accounts so that the corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the carrying value of the depreciable PPE; and



Compel the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with complete description and cost of road network projects to the preparation of Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network (RPCLRN).

We recommended that Management:

Include in the appropriations the titling of the land owned by the Municipality;

Make a representation with the Land Registration Authority to confirm the ownership of all land properties and thereafter, secure copies of the Torrens Title or any equivalent document relative thereto;

Ensure proper safekeeping of the newly secured and subsequently acquired Land Titles; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to record the properties over which the Municipality has acquired absolute ownership.

We recommended that Management:

The MGSO and/or concerned department to observe the proper inventory and monitoring of all procured relief goods taking into consideration the RDS evidencing the issuance to the end-users/beneficiaries;

The concerned department to submit immediately the duly accomplished RDS as supporting document for the relief goods distributed, otherwise, the undocumented distribution shall be suspended or disallowed in audit;

We likewise recommended that Management stop the practice of procuring goods and services on reimbursement basis, except petty purchases to be paid out of the petty cash fund and ensure full compliance with the posting and reporting requirement as provided in the DBM LBC No. 125.

We recommended that Management require the:

Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with Section 6 of COA Circular No. 2012-001;

BAC to justify the noted deficiencies and in its future transactions to strictly comply with the provisions enumerated in Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; 

General Services Officer to submit computation on how many square feet were used in each window, glass door, etc. for the procured 3,066 square feet of blinds, chains and fixtures; and

Contractor to comply with the information needed for the sales invoice.

