We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain complete and updated PPE ledger cards especially for Land, Construction in Progress and Infrastructure Asset accounts to support the GL accounts balance; 


Direct the Municipal Accountant to continue tracing back prior years’ acquisitions of PPE to have a complete detail of the PPE accounts so that the corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the carrying value of the depreciable PPE; and

Continue exerting efforts in completing the physical count and in having a complete and accurate RPCPPE in relation to the deficiencies noted.

We recommended that Management:

Make a representation with the Land Registration Authority to confirm the ownership of all land properties and thereafter, secure copies of the Torrens Title or any equivalent document relative thereto; 
Ensure proper safekeeping of the newly secured and subsequently acquired Land Titles; 
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Inventory Team to exert extra efforts in reconstructing pertinent real property records in order that Subsidiary Ledger Cards of real property owned by the Municipality can be established and maintained; and 
Require the Municipal Accountant to record the properties over which the Municipality has acquired absolute ownership.

We recommended that Management prepare and issue a well-defined set of policies and guidelines governing the implementation of AICS program which must be aligned with the guidelines issued by the Department of Social Welfare and Development governing the grants of AICS.  The policies and guidelines may contain the following:

Kind of financial assistance (burial, transportation, medical, educational, food, shelter and others); 
Limitations on the amounts given per kind of financial assistance; 
Criteria in granting the financial assistance and the documentary requirements for each particular case; and 
Well defined roles and responsibilities of the officials processing requests.

We recommended that Management:

Expedite the completion/updating of the 10-year Municipal Solid Waste Management (SWM) Plan for approval by the National Solid Waste Management Council to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction; 

Provide the necessary fund and training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized; 

Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation; and 


Exert continuous effort in preserving and protecting the environment by implementing the environmental laws as mandated under RA No. 9003.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendations that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain SLs of all the cash advances and receivable accounts for each fund, i.e. General Fund, SEF and Trust Fund, to easily determine the accountability of the officers and employees at any given time which shall also be reconciled periodically to the controlling accounts in the GL; 

Exhaust all possible means to require the concerned officers and employees to liquidate/settle immediately their outstanding cash advances by demanding the immediate submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports or to refund the cash still in their possession; 

Demand for the full liquidation of the amount from the Regular Disbursing Officers and if warranted, be relieved from their designation as Disbursing Officers until such time the amount is fully liquidated; 

Immediately stop the grant of additional cash advances to all officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances until such time that previous cash advances are fully settled as required under Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and Paragraphs 4.1.2 and 4.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002; 

Strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure correct recording of cash advances and timely submission of liquidation documents for full accounting of balances of all cash advances; and 

Institute appropriate legal actions/sanctions such as suspension of salaries of those erring accountable officers/employees for the continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, if warranted.

We recommended that Management: 

Set up a Petty Cash Fund (PCF) sufficient for the non-recurring, emergency and petty expenses of the LGU for one month at the beginning of the year separate from other ordinary cash advances; 

Maintain a separate cashbook for the PCF for ease of record keeping and data retrieval; 

Ensure the proper accomplishment and preparation of petty cash vouchers and its supporting documents; and  

Adhere to the other provisions of Section 48, Volume I of the NGAS Manual for LGUs and Section 2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 in order that the PCF may be managed and controlled properly.

